Date: 17 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada [edited]
[A] Update 33 - Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome 17 Apr 2003 4:30 PM
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/sars/update33.html>

As of 17 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 306 probable
or suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in
Canada. There have been 13 deaths in Canada. To date, transmission
has been limited to specific transmission settings such as
households, hospitals, and specific community settings. This update
is based on the information available to Health Canada at this time.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario is reporting 123 probable and 128 suspect cases. All cases
have occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact
with SARS cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 4 probable and 39 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.
So far, 100 people have been discharged from hospitals in Ontario.
These people were treated as suspect cases or as probable cases.
These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM EDST 17 Apr 2003.
[B] From the 16 Apr 2003 Health Professional's update available at:
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030416_e.html>
The current evidence suggests that respiratory droplet transmission,
requiring close contact with a case of SARS, is the predominant mode
of transmission.
In the province of Ontario the majority of cases have been associated
with specific transmission settings, such as household, hospital, and
specific community groups or settings. There are currently 30 cases
reported amongst approximately 500 members of a religious group in
Toronto. The index case of this community cluster is linked to the
first hospital cluster. The disease spread to a total of 14 members
of the index case's extended family as well as to other members of
the religious group. The key transmission settings include a
gathering held 28-29 Mar 2003, the funeral visitation for the index
case held on 3 Apr 2003, and other social gatherings during and after
these dates. Local health authorities have implemented isolation of
all contacts of suspect and probable cases, including all 500 members
of the religious group, in an effort to contain any further spread
within and outside of this social network. Case finding and contact
tracing efforts in the group are continuing.
[There is an excellent epidemic curve contained in the full article
at
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030416_e.html>
showing the number of cases by date of onset of illness and type of
contact transmission. - Mod.MPP]
