Source: News briefs [edited]
[A] India - Goa submitted on 17 Apr 2003 by Dr Rana Jawad Asghar
<jawad@alumni.washington.edu>
India has recorded its first confirmed case of the deadly SARS virus,
officials from the National Institute of Virology said Thursday. "We
have received a sample from Goa and it is positive for the corona
virus that is responsible for SARS," said Dr A.C. Mishra, director of
the institute in the western city of Pune. The case involved a man in
the western state of Goa, officials said. "He fell sick 2 days ago.
He is from Goa, but he had been travelling in Hong Kong, Singapore,
Bombay, and then returned to Goa," he said.
[Another newswire report from the Hindustani Times
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/181_235567,0008.htm> gave the
following additional information:
SARS has finally hit India, with the government on Thursday
announcing that the virus has been found in the blood, urine, and
sputum samples of a 32-year-old marine engineer in Goa, who is,
however, no longer infective. The marine engineer came to Mumbai on
29 Mar 2003 after a tour of Singapore. He reached Goa on 2 Apr 2003.
"The confirmed SARS patient is being treated in the Goa Medical
College hospital in isolation and is asymptomatic," Director General
of Health Services Dr SP Agarwal told reporters. His contacts,
including his wife (who had travelled with him to Singapore) and
father, are all right and do not have any symptoms, Agarwal said. The
patient had sailed in a ship from Hong Kong and reached Singapore on
30 Mar 2003. He was in Bangkok for 13 hours. He came back to India
and stayed in Mumbai for 3 days. The patient reached Goa on 1 Apr
2003, Agarwal said. He reported with fever and cough on 8 Apr 2003 to
a private doctor and was admitted in Goa Medical College on 10 Apr
2003, Agarwal said, adding the patient responded to conventional
antibiotic treatment and was discharged 2 days later with "home
quarantine" advice. The chest X-ray was normal. However, his blood,
urine, and sputum samples were sent to NIV [National Institute of
Virology], Pune as a precautionary measure, he said. "The tests
confirmed last night that the samples had the new coronavirus that is
causing the SARS epidemic." he said.
[The dates given in the second newswire are a bit confusing and make
it hard to distinguish which case is being referred to, but the
travel dates and the dates of illness are inconsistent. - Mod.MPP]
[B] China - Shanxi from <http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/ED18Ad01.html>
In Shanxi province in central China, in just one hospital in the
provincial capital of Taiyuan alone, there are more than 40 SARS
patients. Owing to its SARS situation worsening significantly in
recent weeks, Shanxi has become a major source of concern. On [15 Apr
2003] the province announced that it had 82 infected patients, 20
times the infection rate in March. As of [15 Apr 2003] 7 people had
died.
Locals say that at most, hospitals have 2 or 3 patients a day. It is
believed that there have been at least 30 suspected SARS cases and 3
deaths in Qingxu. The earliest case of SARS in Qingxu county is said
to be [an individual] of Mayu town, who was infected while in
Guangdong province in February 2003 on official business. Then in
March 2003 an official from the local political consultative
conference went to visit SARS patients in Beijing, during which he
was infected with SARS.
In fact, in early March the World Health Organization (WHO) had
already listed Shanxi as an affected area, with 4 SARS cases. As of
[15 Apr 2003] the number had reached 82 cases. According to a doctor
at Taiyuan Medical University Hospital, his university-affiliated
hospital alone has already treated more than 40 SARS patients, and it
is not even a hospital specializing in SARS. At the Taiyuan Municipal
Infection Hospital it is even more serious.
The earliest case of SARS in Taiyuan was a woman. In March 2003 she
went to Guangdong on official business, and in Taiyuan her diagnosis
was inconclusive. [She] went to Beijing for medical treatment, and
her parents, who were infected while they cared for her, both
ultimately succumbed to SARS. During her treatment, 10 others were
infected.
[Byline: Miao Ye]
[C] China, Ningxia province from Reuters Health News 17 Apr 2003
<http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story2&cid=570&ncid=753&e=6&u=/nm/20030417/sc_nm/health_pneumonia_dc>
There was more evidence that not all cases in China were being
reported to the WHO, and a fresh report that the disease is
spreading. The government declared one infection in the remote
western region of Ningxia, but a doctor there said there were 8.
[Ningxia Hue Autonomous Region shares its western border with Inner
Mongolia, where there have been reports of 10 probable cases; see WHO
Weekly Epidemiologic Record 17 Apr 2003 at:
<http://www.who.int/wer/pdf/2003/wer7816.pdf> and ProMED-mail
posting SARS - worldwide (45): cases 20030412.0890 - Mod.MPP]
[D] Bulgaria report denied 17 Apr 2003
<http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=21710>
The Bulgarian Health Ministry [on 16 Apr 2003] denied the reports of
a case of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in Bulgaria.
According to the Bulgarian News Agency, the woman referred to in the
reports of a local radio station has been diagnosed with probable
pneumonia. The woman has had contact with a diplomat who returned
from China 10 days [ago?], but the diplomat is said to show none of
the symptoms of the disease.
"The Chinese Government is taking all measures to contain the spread
of atypical pneumonia, and thanks to these measures, the epidemic is
under effective control," China's Embassy said in the press release.
The Embassy added that it is not right to suspect every person coming
from China of having atypical pneumonia.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There continues to be significant newswire coverage of the
transmission in Ontario, Canada, along with which comes much
speculation and concern about more widespread community transmission.
The data shown on the Health Canada website do not support this
concern. However, it would be of interest to see a diagrammatic
representation of the various transmission trees of generations of
cases that have been identified in Ontario.
The Morbidity and Mortality weekly report issued by CDC today (see
[5] [B]) draws attention to the need to revise triage protocols for
early identification of possible suspected cases of SARS presenting
to the outpatient sector. It also is significant that probable cases
are now shown separately from suspected cases, so that reports from
the USA will now be comparable to those from other countries.
Additional newswire reports discuss the one or 2 cases reported from
India (the newswires were confusing). There was also a series of
newswires mentioning a suspected case in a contact of a traveller to
China, occurring in Bulgaria, which has been publicly denied by the
Bulgarian Ministry of Health. - Mod.MPP]
